Motivation

Many phenotypes (traits) in agriculture are quantitative in nature. Variation in such quantitative traits is often due to the effects of multiple genetic loci as well as environmental factors. Knowledge of the number, locations, effects, direction, and identities of such genetic loci (called quantitative trait loci, QTL) can lead to new biological insights and support marker-assisted selection breeding programs.

The so-called QTL studies are focused on a central goal: associate genetic variation with phenotypic variation. Or, in another words, associated variation at the DNA level (molecular markers) with variations observed at the field level, using a statistical genomic model. When regions in the genome show convincing evidence of association, we flag them as QTL.

QTL mapping has experienced notable shifts in popularity and application over the past few decades. In the 1990s and early 2000s, with the advent of molecular markers like RFLPs, SSRs, and later SNPs, QTL mapping became a foundational tool in plant and animal genetics. During this period, numerous studies used biparental mapping populations (such as Fâ, backcrosses, RILs) to identify loci associated with traits of interest. This led to a âboomâ in QTL studies across many species.

However, in the 2010s, the rise of genome-wide association studies (GWAS), powered by high-throughput genotyping and large, diverse panels, led to a decline in the use of classical QTL mapping. GWAS offered higher mapping resolution and was seen as more relevant for understanding variation in natural or breeding populations.

More recently, though, there has been a renewed interest in QTL mapping, especially in combination with modern sequencing technologies and multi-parent populations (like MAGIC and NAM). Researchers have recognized the value of QTL mapping for uncovering causal variants in controlled genetic backgrounds and for studying epistatic interactions and rare alleles that GWAS may miss. Additionally, QTL data are increasingly being integrated with genomic prediction models, gene expression (eQTL), and systems biology approaches, which further boosts their relevance.

Advantages and limitations

QTL mapping, unlike GWAS (which will be discussed in future classes), is primarily based on experimental crosses. This approach offers several key advantages:

  • It allows for greater control over phenotyping accuracy, environmental conditions, and the genetic background of the population.
  • Crossing two (or more) parental lines helps randomize genetic variation in the progeny, making it easier to attribute detected associations to causal loci.
  • Due to the simplified genetic structure of experimental populations, researchers can apply more complex statistical models, including those that detect epistasis (interactions between genes).

However, there are also important limitations:

  • QTL mapping typically has lower resolution compared to GWAS, due to limited recombination events in the mapping population.
  • QTL identified in one mapping population may not be transferable or relevant to other populations or natural settings, limiting their broader application.
  • It captures only the genetic variation segregating between the specific parents used, potentially missing important alleles present in broader germplasm.

In short, QTL mapping in experimental crosses is an excellent first step towards more expensive investigations. The simple genetic structure of experimental crosses provides a relatively tractable framework to study the conceptual and statistical principles of genetic mapping.

Roadmap for QTL Analyses

QTL Methods

Single Marker Analysis

The simplest method for the analysis of QTLs is to consider each marker individually and independently from each other, split the individuals into groups, according to their genotypes at the marker, and compare the groupsâ phenotype averages.

Advantages:

  • The key advantage of marker regression is its simplicity: we just perform a t test or ANOVA at each marker.
  • No special software is required (lm function in R can be used).
  • Does not require a previous linkage genetic map.
  • Can be applied to non-linked markers.
  • Theoretical basis of the genome-wide association studies (GWAS).

Disadvantages:

  • Cannot inspect positions between markers.
  • Poor information about QTL location.
  • Model single QTL, which does not allow for more complex models including epistasis or other interactions.

Standard (or Simple) Interval Mapping (IM)

The IM method allows systematically exploration of the genome in search of QTLs. Statistically, it is an extension of the analysis of each single marker, allowing analysis at intervals of markers across the linkage groups. The computational and statistical implementation proposed by Haley and Knott (1992) and Martinez and Curnow (1992), at the same year, became popular in the literature since they described a fast approximation of the ordinary least square (OLS) method.

Advantages:

  • Better inference about the QTL position.
  • Increase of the statistical power.

Disadvantages:

  • Excludes effects of other QTLs linked to the region being tested, so it can result in false positives (called âghostsâ QTL).
  • Does not use all the genome information in the analyzes simultaneously.

Composite Interval Mapping (CIM)

So far, all methods above search for single-QTL: we hypothesized the presence of a single QTL in each position in the genome, one at a time. The model can be improved including a nearby marker as a covariate in further analysis, in order to reduce the residual variation and so improve our ability to detect QTL. Statistically, single regression models become multiple regression models, by the inclusion of other markers in the model as covariates. CIM is the most popular QTL mapping approach and has been widely used in animal, plant and human research.

Advantages:

  • Reduce residual variation and so give increased power to detect QTL.
  • Uses all genome information in the analysis.

Disadvantages:

  • Inefficient to model more complex scenarios considering interaction effects.

Multiple Interval Mapping (MIM)

At this point, some comments are necessary. All previous methods have considered the follow question: âIs there a QTL linked to this marker or interval?â. For this, the first approach (single marker analysis) considered each marker individually, without previous information about linkage groups. The IM method uses a similar regression model but considering prior linkage mapping information to fit the model. Finally, the CIM approach fitted a multiple regression model assuming other molecular markers as covariates in the regression model. An alternative question is:âAre there QTL here and there?â. This is the idea behind of the MIM method. Briefly, MIM is a method that simultaneously considers multiples QTLs. For this purpose, multiple procedures to compare and select models are necessary. As pointed out by K. Broman: âQTL mapping is best viewed as a model selection or variable selection problem: what set of loci (and QTL Ã QTL interactions) are best supported by the data? â. Modern studies of QTL mapping have been based in this theory

Advantages:

  • Combines high precision and statistical power
  • Inclusion of epistasis and other interactions sources in the model.
  • Better description of the genetic architecture of a quantitative trait.
  • Estimate the number, position, effects and interaction between QTLs
